flowRoot.flowPara: Uses a select then act workflow, which allows content to be selected without being forced through a preview step.
Has a number of implications for the design of Files: 1. Requires the use of an action bar. 2. Obsoletes the need for selection mode.
Preview button acts as a toggle.
Floating back/forward buttons allow browsing through content. Browsing order follows what is visible in the content grid.
The selection moves with as you browse, so that the visible content item is always selected.
When multiple content items are being selected, preview does not allow browsing. Selection can be toggled by clicking the content items.
Allows selecting a content item without being forced to preview first.
Inconsistency between single and multiple select.
Floating back/forward buttons allow browsing through content items. Browsing order follows what is visible in the content grid.
Vertical scrolling allows browsing within multi-page documents.
When multiple content items are being selected, preview does not allow browsing between or within multipage documents. Selection can be toggled by clicking the content items.
TO DO: how to handle more than two items? What about items of different types? What about items with multiple pages?
Could be a bit limiting to only be able to preview selected items - what if you want to preview items that you are considering for selection?
One alternative - preview begins at the last selected item, but then you can browse through any content item.
Another alternative - two actions on each content item - one to select, and one to preview. This would replace the need for a preview button.

Problems with that approach - 1. lack of symmetry with Files (unless we use the same approach there). 2. Makes the whole thing more complex and potentially error-prone, particularly for single selections, which is probably the most common case.
